# {{WORKER_DISPLAY_NAME}} — macOS-specific notes

The macOS-only answers from the interview, plus packaging caveats for the `.app` (or single-binary) build. Anything that's true regardless of OS lives in `../AUTHORING.md`; the worker's spec lives in `../WORKER.md`. This file is for the macOS-specific pieces only.

If the same worker is later built on a different OS, a sibling folder (`../windows/` or `../linux/`) gets its own `<os>-specific.md`. Those files are independent of this one — don't try to factor common bits across them.

## OS-specific interview answers

- **Host OS at forge time:** macOS (record the version — `sw_vers -productVersion` — if it mattered for a decision).
- **Chip:** Apple Silicon / Intel (matters for which Python wheels PyInstaller picks up).
- **UI framework picked on macOS:** SwiftUI / Electron + Tailwind / Tauri / PySide6 / Tkinter / other. Default and first-recommended is **native SwiftUI** (~5–15 MB binary — smallest deliverable and the closest match for the Claude-Code-style look). Offer Electron + Tailwind only if `npm` is on the `PATH` (~80–150 MB — bundles Chromium); offer Tauri only if a Rust toolchain is on the `PATH` (~5–20 MB — uses the system webview). Record the framework the user picked **and the size estimate they agreed to**; if they didn't take the native default, note why (wanted a webview UI, preferred a Python-only stack, etc.).
- **Data location:** the actual path the worker writes to. Convention is `~/Library/Application Support/<worker-slug>/` for per-user state; deviate only when the user asked for it.
- **Scheduler glue:** none / launchd `.plist` in `resources/` / Login Items entry / loops internally. If launchd, link to the `.plist` and note where the user should `cp` it (`~/Library/LaunchAgents/`).
- **Local-model runtime:** Ollama (default) / Apple Foundation Models / MLX / other. Note the models pulled for each LOCAL unit (`llama3.2:3b`, `llava`, etc.).
- **Keychain backend:** macOS Keychain via `keyring`. Default — record an alternative only if the user explicitly asked for one.

## Packaging notes

- Default build: PyInstaller `--onefile --windowed` (or drop `--windowed` for CLI workers).
- For a real `.app` bundle with proper Info.plist and Finder integration, use py2app instead — note in this section if the user asked for that.
- The display-name string is what names the `.app` bundle — quoted in the PyInstaller command because it usually has spaces.
- **Gatekeeper warning on first launch.** Unsigned `.app` bundles trigger "can't open because Apple cannot check it for malicious software." The user can right-click → Open the first time to bypass. Make sure this is mentioned in the recipient-facing `../WORKER.md` setup section so it doesn't look like the worker is broken.
- If the worker is universal vs. arch-specific (Apple Silicon only), note it here — recipients on the other arch will need to know.
- Anything else worth knowing for the next macOS reforge.

